04386nam a22006135i 9780292744318DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212013txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927443187 a10.7560/7443012doi  a(DE-B1597)588319  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 7aPER0000002bisacsh04a791.43/65521 aGoldman, Eric A., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe American Jewish Story through Cinema /cEric A. Goldman. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (264 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface. Film as Haggadah: Toward a Better Understanding of America’s Jews -- tChapter 1 Introduction: A Century of American Jewish Life -- tChapter 2 The Jazz Singer: Out of the Jewish Ghetto (The 1920s) -- tChapter 3. Gentleman’s Agreement and Crossfire: Films That Took on Anti- Semitism in 1947 (The 1940s) -- tChapter 4 The Young Lions: Guaranteeing Acceptance (The 1950s) -- tChapter 5 The Way We Were and The Prince of Tides: Barbra Streisand and the Evolving American Jewish Woman (The 1970s And 1980s) -- tChapter 6 Avalon and Liberty Heights: The Spirit of Family—Remembering Better (The 1990s) -- tChapter 7 Everything Is Illuminated: A New Direction in Film—Searching for a Usable Past (The Twenty- first century) -- tNotes -- tSelected Bibliography -- tSelected Filmography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aLike the haggadah, the traditional “telling” of the story of the Israelites’ exodus from Egypt that is read at the Passover seder, cinema offers a valuable text from which to gain an understanding of the social, political, and cultural realities of Jews in America. In an industry strongly influenced by Jewish filmmakers who made and continue to make the decisions as to which films are produced, the complex and evolving nature of the American Jewish condition has had considerable impact on American cinema and, in particular, on how Jews are reflected on the screen. This groundbreaking study analyzes select mainstream films from the beginning of the sound era to today to provide an understanding of the American Jewish experience over the last century. In the first half of the twentieth century, Hollywood’s movie moguls, most of whom were Jewish, shied away from asserting a Jewish image on the screen for fear that they might be too closely identified with that representation. Over the next two decades, Jewish moviemakers became more comfortable with the concept of a Jewish hero and with an overpowered, yet heroic, Israel. In time, the Holocaust assumed center stage as the single event with the greatest effect on American Jewish identity. Recently, as American Jewish screenwriters, directors, and producers have become increasingly comfortable with their heritage, we are seeing an unprecedented number of movies that spotlight Jewish protagonists, experiences, and challenges.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aJews in motion pictures. 0aJews in the motion picture industryzUnited States. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/74430140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292744318423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292744318/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK